# DedgeAuth Integration

This project uses **DedgeAuth** for authentication. DedgeAuth is the central auth server for all FK web applications.

DedgeAuth source: `C:\opt\src\DedgeAuth` | Full integration docs: `C:\opt\src\DedgeAuth\docs\integration\`

## Server Portability

All apps are designed to run on **any server** without code changes. When deploying to a new environment:

1. Update `appsettings.json` -> `DedgeAuth:AuthServerUrl` to the new DedgeAuth URL
2. Run `IIS-DeployApp.ps1` on the new server — it creates the IIS virtual app and registers in DedgeAuth DB from the deploy template (`*.deploy.json` DedgeAuth block)
4. No HTML, JavaScript, or C# code changes needed

The current DedgeAuth installation is on `dedge-server` (test environment). **NEVER hardcode this hostname** in runtime code (C#, HTML, JS). It belongs ONLY in `appsettings.json` and build/deploy infrastructure (`.pubxml`, `Build-And-Publish.ps1`).

## Deployment (IIS-DeployApp)

This app is deployed as an IIS virtual application using the standard two-step process:

1. `Build-And-Publish.ps1` publishes to staging: `\\<server>\DedgeCommon\Software\DedgeWinApps\<AppName>`
2. `IIS-DeployApp.ps1` (in `C:\opt\src\DedgePsh\DevTools\WebSites\IIS-DeployApp\`) copies to local install path and creates IIS virtual app

All FK web apps (DedgeAuth, DocView, GenericLogHandler, ServerMonitorDashboard) follow this pattern and run as virtual applications under `Default Web Site` on the same IIS server.

## Backend (Program.cs)

```csharp
using DedgeAuth.Client.Extensions;
using DedgeAuth.Client.Endpoints;

builder.Services.AddDedgeAuth(builder.Configuration);
// ...
// UseRouting() is implicit in .NET 6+ minimal hosting — do NOT call it explicitly
app.UseDedgeAuth();         // token/code extraction + JWT auth + session validation + visit tracking + redirect
app.UseDefaultFiles();
app.UseStaticFiles();
app.MapControllers();
app.MapDedgeAuthProxy();    // registers /api/DedgeAuth/me, /api/DedgeAuth/logout, and /api/DedgeAuth/ui/{path} proxy
```

- Do NOT call `UseAuthentication()` or `UseAuthorization()` separately — `UseDedgeAuth()` handles both.
- Do NOT add `builder.Services.AddHttpClient()` — `AddDedgeAuth()` registers it.

## HTML Pages

All FK apps run as IIS virtual applications (e.g. at `/MyApp`). **ALL** `href` and `src` references in HTML must use **relative paths** (no leading `/`) — this applies to DedgeAuth proxy assets AND the app's own CSS/JS. Absolute paths like `/css/app.css` resolve from the site root and 404 under a virtual path.

DedgeAuth assets are served through a local proxy (`MapDedgeAuthProxy()`) — do NOT hardcode server URLs, do NOT copy files locally:

```html
<!-- App CSS — relative path, no leading / -->
<link rel="stylesheet" href="css/app.css">
<!-- DedgeAuth assets — via local proxy -->
<link rel="stylesheet" href="api/DedgeAuth/ui/common.css">
<!-- Optional: tenant fallback for when theme.css is empty or unreachable (see css-fallback-plan.md) -->
<!-- <link rel="stylesheet" href="api/DedgeAuth/ui/tenant-fallback.css"> -->
<style id="DedgeAuth-tenant-css"></style>
<link rel="stylesheet" href="api/DedgeAuth/ui/user.css">
<!-- ... -->
<div id="DedgeAuthUserMenu"></div>
<!-- ... -->
<script src="api/DedgeAuth/ui/user.js"></script>
<!-- App JS — relative path, no leading / -->
<script src="js/app.js"></script>
```

The proxy fetches from `AuthServerUrl` and caches for 1 hour. Relative paths ensure correct resolution under IIS virtual application paths.

## Configuration (appsettings.json)

Required `DedgeAuth` section: `Enabled`, `AuthServerUrl`, `JwtSecret`, `JwtIssuer`, `JwtAudience`, `AppId`.
Default proxy route prefix: `/api/DedgeAuth` (PascalCase F and A — must match).

## Authorization

Use `[RequireAppPermission("Admin")]` for role-based access or standard `[Authorize]`.

## Code Signing

The `.csproj` must include DedgeSign targets for Release builds. See `C:\opt\src\DedgeAuth\docs\integration\setup-guide.md` Step 8.
